3. SCOPE OF SERVICES
1. Design and Development of new SAP BTP interface by using SAP BTP Integration
Suite.
2. Design and Development of new ETL requirements from Unilever Business by using
SAP BODS.
3. Changes/Enhancements to the existing SAP BODS Components/Objects based on
Business requirements from Unilever.
4. Coordination with respective teams for Release management, Change Management
coordination and transport related activities.
5. Alignment with all the Platform teams ,3rd party and other connected systems on the
timelines, test support and go-live activities.
6. Cutover Preparation and coordination
7. 100 % connectivity testing for all applications.
8. UAT Support and coordination with

r Preparation and coordination
7. 100 % connectivity testing for all applications.
8. UAT Support and coordination with the teams.
9. Regression test Support and Analysis.
10. Coordinate with SAP admin and Basis.
11. Coordination with SAP AM teams to update the Partner Profile, end point checks, dry
run etc.,
12. RefDB entries testing and update into the new environments.
13. Project Management to work with client stakeholders for demand management,
capacity planning and demand intake and keep tracker for activities like demands, effort
estimation etc.
Project Activities - Out of Scope
Apart from above Project activities rest of all will be considered as Out of Scope.

INITIAL UNDERSTANDING
UNILEVER is seeking a trusted partner to coordinate the Dynamics 365 F&O implementation for Nutrafol – Phase 1. As a global leader in the
consumer goods market, Unilever is embarking on a critical technological transformation and requires an experienced consultancy to provide
expert project coordination and leadership for the D365 ERP rollout, specifically ensuring that the technical aspects are delivered effectively by
all involved teams.
Period: October 07, 2024 to June 30, 2025
Project: D365 F&O – Phase 1
Objective:
This engagement focuses on the smooth coordination of the Dynamics 365 ERP system implementation, transitioning from Quickbooks to the
new solution, with a key milestone in April 2025 aligned with audit remediation efforts.
Key Responsibilities:
Project and Stakeholder Management: Take ownership of the overall coordination of the technical workstreams, ensuring alignment with
Unilever’s objectives and timely communication with all key stakeholders. Facilitate discussions, manage expectations, and ensure smooth
collaboration between teams.
Schedule and Risk Management: Develop and maintain a detailed project schedule that tracks key

aboration between teams.
Schedule and Risk Management: Develop and maintain a detailed project schedule that tracks key milestones and deliverables. Identify and
assess potential risks, implementing mitigation strategies while maintaining transparency with stakeholders about project progress and issues.
Governance and Quality Assurance: Establish governance frameworks that ensure all technical deliverables are managed according to PMI
and PMBOK standards. Oversee quality management processes to ensure the project remains on track and deliverables meet the required
standards, without directly executing the technical tasks.
Lead the coordination of all technical teams, ensuring that each phase of the project is executed efficiently by Unilever's internal resources and
third-party vendors.
Serve as the point of contact between Unilever’s D365 F&O Tech team and the system integrators, ensuring smooth communication, alignment
of goals, and timely decision-making.

Unilever’s assets, including (but not limited to) our information, brands, IT systems, employees and our
business processes/objectives.

and practices designed to protect networks, computers, programs and data from attack, damage or
unauthorized access. Such controls are in place to prevent/limit harm to Unilever’s systems and data, as
well as to individuals or brands in financial, intellectual or

Intended Audience
This document is for Suppliers with access to or who support Unilever’s data and/or systems. It is expected
that specific IT and/or Cybersecurity roles at the Supplier will fulfil the responsibilities described, with
support from other resources e.g. business continuity experts, crisis management experts.

What to Report
All Suppliers engaged by Unilever are required to report actual / confirmed breaches or compromises
affecting Unilever Data, or environments where Unilever Data is stored and handled.
Examples of such security events may include (but are not limited to) any of the following:
Compromised computing resources, which includes:
• System (OS) account compromises
• User account compromises
• Point-of-sale intrusions
Email-facilitated compromise resulting from:
• Unsolicited Commercial Email (UCE), more commonly known as “spam”
• Phishing Emails seeking recipient’s user credentials or personal information
Attacks

), more commonly known as “spam”
• Phishing Emails seeking recipient’s user credentials or personal information
Attacks on web applications through:
• Cross site scripting (XSS)
• SQL injection
• DDoS attacks
Network and network resource incidents, including:
• Network scanning activity
• Denial of Service attacks
Resource misconfiguration incidents, including:
• Attacks on open proxy servers and anonymous FTP servers
• Vulnerable software configurations that may result in a future compromise
• Abuse via web forms and blog sites
• Misuse of licensed resources
Malware related attacks such as:
• Ransomware
Worm infections to significant number of users
• Copyright Infringement Reports
• Misuse of privileges by rogue employee or other insiders
• Physical Loss or Theft of Equipment
• Major business disruption (Disaster Recovery scenario)
Legally Reportable Incidents
This guideline does not supersede any local, national or international legal requirements regarding
Incident notification and does not absolve Suppliers from any other compliance responsibilities to notify
different Unilever stakeholders.
When to Report It
Unilever requires that Suppliers provide an alert to Unilever’s Inte

different Unilever stakeholders.
When to Report It
Unilever requires that Suppliers provide an alert to Unilever’s Intelligent Security Operations Centre
(referred to as ISOC henceforth) as per contractual guidelines. Suppliers with inherent infrastructure (such as
SaaS and PaaS suppliers) are not expected to submit a formal Incident investigation; however, an
Incident notification is a mandatory requirement.
The table below in Appendix A provides an indication of how Unilever will internally classify the severity of
cybersecurity Incidents. This information is provided to aid Suppliers in accurately reporting Incidents
involving Unilever Data or systems. The Unilever ISOC Manager will make the ultimate decision on
Unilever’s classification with respect to Incident priority.
How to Report It
All investigations should be reported to Unilever’s ISOC (Intelligent Security Operations Centre) at E-mail:

Incident Investigation Approach
Unilever expects all Suppliers to conduct their investigations in line with their own f

Incident Investigation Approach
Unilever expects all Suppliers to conduct their investigations in line with their own formally documented
procedures. Unilever may request further information in relation to an Incident in order to seek assurance
that adequate investigation and remediation measures have been undertaken.
The responsibility for an investigation by a Supplier should be handled by a technically competent “Cyber
Security Investigation Lead” or equivalent role. The Supplier’s Investigation Lead is responsible for
undertaking a thorough Incident analysis, including use of forensic techniques where appropriate and
identifying those corrective actions required. The Investigation Lead is required to submit complete root
cause analysis to Unilever Security Operations Centre.
Unilever reserves the right to engage with the affected Supplier and actively support any cyber Incident
investigation where justified by the:
1) Criticality of the Unilever Data affected.
2) Impact to the Unilever Operations.
3) Potential reputational impact to Unilever.
4) Impact on Unilever’s compliance with Government and regulatory requirements.
